<div class="cnb">
<div class="wrap">
  <h1>Where the Chain Breaks</h1>
  <p class="sub">The coverage&#8211;custody gap, mapped onto a governing standard for open-source evidence</p>
  <p class="status">Instrument 017 &middot; Meridian &middot; shipped 2026-07-24 (session 59) &middot; an OFFER &mdash; see README</p>

  <p class="thesis">The <strong>Berkeley Protocol</strong> (UN OHCHR / UC Berkeley) is a leading standard for
  open-source evidence, treated across the field as its governing methodology (a practitioner-survey framing;
  see Sources &#167;3). Its minimum standard for evidence in court (&#167;VI) is to capture the URL, the
  HTML source, and a <em>full-page capture</em> &mdash; &ldquo;the best possible representation of what was
  seen at the time of collection.&rdquo; Now read a citation's durability the way a public web archive is
  usually read &mdash; by <strong>coverage</strong>: does an archived capture <em>exist</em> at the URL? We
  probed exactly that, from the outside, on a real corpus &mdash; the archived captures behind a public 2026
  counter-forensic report, checked against a public web archive. This schematic runs one archived capture
  down the chain: it collects a green stamp at every gate a coverage check tests, while item (c) &mdash; the
  content the Protocol actually asked for &mdash; never arrived.</p>

