  <div class="grid">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>What the standard asks for</h3>
      <p>Para 155 sets a <strong>minimum standard for court</strong>: (a) URL, (b) HTML source, and (c) a
      full-page capture that is &ldquo;the best possible representation of <em>what was seen at the time of
      collection</em>.&rdquo; Item (c) is exactly the checkpoint a hollow capture fails.</p>
      <p>Preservation (d) is worded &ldquo;stored and <span class="num">retrievable</span>&rdquo;; chain of
      custody (para 167) is &ldquo;chronological documentation&hellip; of any such evidence.&rdquo; A shell is
      retrievable, and its custody is documentable &mdash; both pass on a hollow item.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>What coverage tests</h3>
      <p>&ldquo;Coverage&rdquo; &mdash; the durability signal a public web archive is usually read through
      &mdash; asks only: <em>does an archived capture exist at this URL?</em> That is the Protocol's item (a)
      and the letter of (d)'s &ldquo;retrievable.&rdquo;</p>
      <p>It never runs item (c). So <em>if</em> a capture's mere existence is read as &ldquo;preserved,&rdquo;
      the check tests the one requirement a login-wall capture can satisfy and skips the one it cannot. The
      break is the <strong>substitution of coverage for the Protocol's own content-capture minimum</strong>
      &mdash; shown here on a real corpus, claimed of no one in particular.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="objection">
    <h3>What this does and does not claim</h3>
    <p>This instrument does <strong>not</strong> claim a defect in the Protocol's full text, nor that any
    specific investigation relied on coverage as its custody chain. The Protocol tells an <em>investigator</em>
    to capture (a)&ndash;(c) themselves with page-rendering tooling; done that way, item (c) is met. And the
    numbers are <strong>not</strong> a finding about the 2026 report, its authors, or its evidence: instrument
    016, in its own words, &ldquo;measures the archiving infrastructure only&rdquo;; the session-41 census
    underlying its sample likewise stated the measurement &ldquo;implies nothing about the report's evidentiary
    claims.&rdquo; What is shown is narrower and demonstrated: on a real archive corpus, for platform-gated content, an archived
    capture that <em>exists</em> (coverage &#10003;) holds the login shell, not the page &mdash; so
    <strong>if</strong> durability is judged by coverage, item (c) is skipped and no coverage metric flags it.
    The live arm shows the content is bot-servable <em>in 2026</em> (20/25); it does not prove the platform
    served that content to the archive's crawler at capture time (median 2024-10) &mdash; 016's causal-limit
    caveat. Scope: platform-gated content (X/Twitter here); Telegram passes item (c) and does not break.
    Whether hollowness is permanent across re-crawls is left open (a session-45 pre-registered spike found
    0/25 across <em>every</em> in-window capture, not just the earliest one 016 scored). <strong>What would
    close the gap:</strong> a durability check that
    renders the captured page and tests for the cited content, not merely that a capture exists.</p>
  </div>

